04208nam a22006135i 9780271090658DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710906587 a10.1515/97802710906582doi  a(DE-B1597)586179  a(OCoLC)1262307221  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0150802bisacsh04a759.52231 aVerstegen, Ian F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFederico Barocci and the Oratorians :bCorporate Patronage and Style in the Counter-Reformation /cIan F. Verstegen. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (192 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies ;v1400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Tables -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: What's in a Style? Barocci and the Oratorians -- tChapter 1: Federico Barocci, Filippo Neri, and Christian Optimism -- tChapter 2: The Altarpiece Cycle: The Rosary and Coordinated Devotion -- tChapter 3: The Visitation and the Presentation of the Virgin -- tChapter 4: The Nativity of the Virgin for the High Altar and the Institution of the Eucharist for the Pope -- tChapter 5: Baroccismo into the Seicento -- tAppendix 1: Chiesa Nuova Altars and the Altarpieces Adorning Them -- tAppendix 2: Chiesa Nuova Timeline -- tAppendix 3: Order of Altarpiece Commissions and Completions -- tAppendix 4: Giovan Battista Guerra's Renovations in the Chiesa Nuova -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1586, Federico Barocci delivered his Visitation of the Virgin and St. Elizabeth to the Chiesa Nuova in Rome. For the next quarter century, Barocci dominated the art scene in Rome; there was no other artist from whom it was harder to get work and no other artist charged such high prices. Having two important altarpieces in the Chiesa Nuova and two additional commissions discussed was an impressive feat for an artist living exclusively in Urbino. Why did the Oratorians monopolize Barocci's talents in Rome and why does it seem that Barocci was their first choice when considering artists to decorate their church? What was it about Barocci's art that appealed to Oratorian sensibilities and their vision of the artistic program for decoration of their church?This book examines the relationship between Barocci and the Congregation of the Oratory, arguing for a distinct physiognomy of Oratorian patronage and exposing the function the Oratorians expected of religious imagery in contrast to other groups of their time. While explaining Oratorian patronage, it thus deals with a thorny question in social science: how can a collective body have unified intentions and actions? The result is a contribution both to the history of Italian painting and to art historical methodology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271090658zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271090658423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271090658.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK